# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: protein-structure
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] An **alpha helix** (or **α-helix**) is a sequence of amino acids in a protein that are twisted into a coil (a helix).
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] The alpha helix is the most common structural arrangement in the secondary structure of proteins.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] It is also the most extreme type of local structure, and it is the local structure that is most easily predicted from a sequence of amino acids.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] The alpha helix has a right-handed helix conformation in which every backbone N−H group hydrogen bonds to the backbone C=O group of the amino acid that is four residues earlier in the protein sequence.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] is at the bottom and its C-terminus at the top.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Note that the sidechains (black stubs) angle slightly downward, toward the N-terminus, while the peptide oxygens (red) point up and the peptide NHs (blue with grey stubs) point down.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] In the early 1930s, William Astbury showed that there were drastic changes in the X-ray fiber diffraction of moist wool or hair fibers upon significant stretching.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] The data suggested that the unstretched fibers had a coiled molecular structure with a characteristic repeat of ≈5.1 ångströms (0.51 nanometres).
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Astbury initially proposed a linked-chain structure for the fibers.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Hans Neurath was the first to show that Astbury's models could not be correct in detail, because they involved clashes of atoms.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Neurath's paper and Astbury's data inspired H.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Taylor, Maurice Huggins and Bragg and collaborators to propose models of keratin that somewhat resemble the modern α-helix.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] The pivotal moment came in the early spring of 1948, when Pauling caught a cold and went to bed.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Being bored, he drew a polypeptide chain of roughly correct dimensions on a strip of paper and folded it into a helix, being careful to maintain the planar peptide bonds.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] After a few attempts, he produced a model with physically plausible hydrogen bonds.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Pauling then worked with Corey and Branson to confirm his model before publication.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] In 1954, Pauling was awarded his first Nobel Prize "for his research into the nature of the chemical bond and its application to the elucidation of the structure of complex substances" (such as proteins), prominently including the structure of the α-helix.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] The amino acids in an α-helix are arranged in a right-handed helical structure where each amino acid residue corresponds to a 100° turn in the helix (i.e., the helix has 3.6 residues per turn), and a translation of 1.5 Å (0.15 nm) along the helical axis.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Dunitz describes how Pauling's first article on the theme in fact shows a left-handed helix, the enantiomer of the true structure.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Short pieces of left-handed helix sometimes occur with a large content of achiral glycine amino acids, but are unfavorable for the other normal, biological L-amino acids.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] The pitch of the alpha-helix (the vertical distance between consecutive turns of the helix) is 5.4 Å (0.54 nm), which is the product of 1.5 and 3.6.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] The most important thing is that the N-H group of one amino acid forms a hydrogen bond with the C=O group of the amino acid *four* residues earlier; this repeated *i* + 4 → *i* hydrogen bonding is the most prominent characteristic of an α-helix.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Official international nomenclature specifies two ways of defining α-helices, rule 6.2 in terms of repeating *φ*, *ψ* torsion angles (see below) and rule 6.3 in terms of the combined pattern of pitch and hydrogen bonding.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] The α-helices can be identified in protein structure using several computational methods, such as DSSP (Define Secondary Structure of Protein).
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Similar structures include the 310 helix (*i* + 3 → *i* hydrogen bonding) and the π-helix (*i* + 5 → *i* hydrogen bonding).
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] The α-helix can be described as a 3.613 helix, since the *i* + 4 spacing adds three more atoms to the H-bonded loop compared to the tighter 310 helix, and on average, 3.6 amino acids are involved in one ring of α-helix.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] The subscripts refer to the number of atoms (including the hydrogen) in the closed loop formed by the hydrogen bond.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Residues in α-helices typically adopt backbone (*φ*, *ψ*) dihedral angles around (−60°, −45°), as shown in the image at right.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] In more general terms, they adopt dihedral angles such that the *ψ* dihedral angle of one residue and the *φ* dihedral angle of the *next* residue sum to roughly −105°.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] As a consequence, α-helical dihedral angles, in general, fall on a diagonal stripe on the Ramachandran diagram (of slope −1), ranging from (−90°, −15°) to (−70°, −35°).
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] For comparison, the sum of the dihedral angles for a 310 helix is roughly −75°, whereas that for the π-helix is roughly −130°.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] The α-helix is tightly packed; there is almost no free space within the helix.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] The amino-acid side-chains are on the outside of the helix, and point roughly "downward" (i.e., toward the N-terminus), like the branches of an evergreen tree (Christmas tree effect).
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] This directionality is sometimes used in preliminary, low-resolution electron-density maps to determine the direction of the protein backbone.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Helices observed in proteins can range from four to over forty residues long, but a typical helix contains about ten amino acids (about three turns).
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] In general, short polypeptides do not exhibit much α-helical structure in solution, since the entropic cost associated with the folding of the polypeptide chain is not compensated for by a sufficient amount of stabilizing interactions.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] In general, the backbone hydrogen bonds of α-helices are considered slightly weaker than those found in β-sheets, and are readily attacked by the ambient water molecules.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] However, in more hydrophobic environments such as the plasma membrane, or in the presence of co-solvents such as trifluoroethanol (TFE), or isolated from solvent in the gas phase, oligopeptides readily adopt stable α-helical structure.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Furthermore, crosslinks can be incorporated into peptides to conformationally stabilize helical folds.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Crosslinks stabilize the helical state by entropically destabilizing the unfolded state and by removing enthalpically stabilized "decoy" folds that compete with the fully helical state.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] It has been shown that α-helices are more stable, robust to mutations and designable than β-strands in natural proteins, and also in artificially designed proteins.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] The three most popular ways of visualizing the alpha-helical secondary structure of oligopeptide sequences are (1) a helical wheel, (2) a wenxiang diagram, and (3) a helical net.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Each of these can be visualized with various software packages and web servers.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] To generate a small number of diagrams, Heliquest can be used for helical wheels, and NetWheels can be used for helical wheels and helical nets.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] To programmatically generate a large number of diagrams, helixvis can be used to draw helical wheels and wenxiang diagrams in the R and Python programming languages.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Since the α-helix is defined by its hydrogen bonds and backbone conformation, the most detailed experimental evidence for α-helical structure comes from atomic-resolution X-ray crystallography such as the example shown at right.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] It is clear that all the backbone carbonyl oxygens point downward (toward the C-terminus) but splay out slightly, and the H-bonds are approximately parallel to the helix axis.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Protein structures from NMR spectroscopy also show helices well, with characteristic observations of nuclear Overhauser effect (NOE) couplings between atoms on adjacent helical turns.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] In some cases, the individual hydrogen bonds can be observed directly as a small scalar coupling in NMR.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] There are several lower-resolution methods for assigning general helical structure.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] The NMR chemical shifts (in particular of the Cα, Cβ and C′) and residual dipolar couplings are often characteristic of helices.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] The far-UV (170–250 nm) circular dichroism spectrum of helices is also idiosyncratic, exhibiting a pronounced double minimum at around 208 and 222 nm.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Infrared spectroscopy is rarely used, since the α-helical spectrum resembles that of a random coil (although these might be discerned by, e.g., hydrogen-deuterium exchange).
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Finally, cryo electron microscopy is now capable of discerning individual α-helices within a protein, although their assignment to residues is still an active area of research.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Long homopolymers of amino acids often form helices if soluble.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Such long, isolated helices can also be detected by other methods, such as dielectric relaxation, flow birefringence, and measurements of the diffusion constant.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] In stricter terms, these methods detect only the characteristic prolate (long cigar-like) hydrodynamic shape of a helix, or its large dipole moment.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Different amino-acid sequences have different propensities for forming α-helical structure.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Alanine, uncharged glutamate, leucine, charged arginine, methionine and charged lysine have especially high helix-forming propensities, whereas proline and glycine have poor helix-forming propensities.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Proline either breaks or kinks a helix, both because it cannot donate an amide hydrogen bond (because it has none) and because its sidechain interferes sterically with the backbone of the preceding turn – inside a helix, which forces a bend of about 30° in the helix's axis.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] However, proline is often the *first* residue of a helix, presumably due to its structural rigidity.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] At the other extreme, glycine also tends to disrupt helices because its high conformational flexibility makes it entropically expensive to adopt the relatively constrained α-helical structure.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Estimated differences in free energy change, Δ(Δ*G*), estimated in kcal/mol per residue in an α-helical configuration, relative to alanine arbitrarily set as zero.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Higher numbers (more positive free energy changes) are less favoured.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Significant deviations from these average numbers are possible, depending on the identities of the neighbouring residues.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] A helix has an overall dipole moment due to the aggregate effect of the individual microdipoles from the carbonyl groups of the peptide bond pointing along the helix axis.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] The effects of this macrodipole are a matter of some controversy. α-helices often occur with the N-terminal end bound by a negatively charged group, sometimes an amino acid side chain such as glutamate or aspartate, or sometimes a phosphate ion.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Some regard the helix macrodipole as interacting electrostatically with such groups.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Others feel that this is misleading and it is more realistic to say that the hydrogen bond potential of the free NH groups at the N-terminus of an α-helix can be satisfied by hydrogen bonding; this can also be regarded as set of interactions between local microdipoles such as C=O···H−N.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Coiled-coil α helices are highly stable forms in which two or more helices wrap around each other in a "supercoil" structure.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Coiled coils contain a highly characteristic sequence motif known as a **heptad repeat**, in which the motif repeats itself every seven residues along the sequence (*amino acid* residues, not DNA base-pairs).
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] The first and especially the fourth residues (known as the *a* and *d* positions) are almost always hydrophobic; the fourth residue is typically leucine – this gives rise to the name of the structural motif called a *leucine zipper*, which is a type of coiled-coil.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] These hydrophobic residues pack together in the interior of the helix bundle.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] In general, the fifth and seventh residues (the *e* and *g* positions) have opposing charges and form a salt bridge stabilized by electrostatic interactions.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Fibrous proteins such as keratin or the "stalks" of myosin or kinesin often adopt coiled-coil structures, as do several dimerizing proteins.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] A pair of coiled-coils – a four-helix bundle – is a very common structural motif in proteins.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] For example, it occurs in human growth hormone and several varieties of cytochrome.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] The Rop protein, which promotes plasmid replication in bacteria, is an interesting case in which a single polypeptide forms a coiled-coil and two monomers assemble to form a four-helix bundle.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] The amino acids that make up a particular helix can be plotted on a helical wheel, a representation that illustrates the orientations of the constituent amino acids (see the article for leucine zipper for such a diagram).
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Changes in binding orientation also occur for facially-organized oligopeptides.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] This pattern is especially common in antimicrobial peptides, and many models have been devised to describe how this relates to their function.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Common to many of them is that the hydrophobic face of the antimicrobial peptide forms pores in the plasma membrane after associating with the fatty chains at the membrane core.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Myoglobin and hemoglobin, the first two proteins whose structures were solved by X-ray crystallography, have very similar folds made up of about 70% α-helix, with the rest being non-repetitive regions, or "loops" that connect the helices.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] In classifying proteins by their dominant fold, the Structural Classification of Proteins database maintains a large category specifically for all-α proteins.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Hemoglobin then has an even larger-scale quaternary structure, in which the functional oxygen-binding molecule is made up of four subunits.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] α-Helices have particular significance in DNA binding motifs, including helix-turn-helix motifs, leucine zipper motifs and zinc finger motifs.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] An example of both aspects is the transcription factor Max (see image at left), which uses a helical coiled coil to dimerize, positioning another pair of helices for interaction in two successive turns of the DNA major groove.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] α-Helices are also the most common protein structure element that crosses biological membranes (transmembrane protein), presumably because the helical structure can satisfy all backbone hydrogen-bonds internally, leaving no polar groups exposed to the membrane if the sidechains are hydrophobic.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Proteins are sometimes anchored by a single membrane-spanning helix, sometimes by a pair, and sometimes by a helix bundle, most classically consisting of seven helices arranged up-and-down in a ring such as for rhodopsins (see image at right) and other G protein–coupled receptors (GPCRs).
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] The structural stability between pairs of α-Helical transmembrane domains rely on conserved membrane interhelical packing motifs, for example, the Glycine-xxx-Glycine (or small-xxx-small) motif.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] α-Helices under axial tensile deformation, a characteristic loading condition that appears in many alpha-helix-rich filaments and tissues, results in a characteristic three-phase behavior of stiff-soft-stiff tangent modulus.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Phase I corresponds to the small-deformation regime during which the helix is stretched homogeneously, followed by phase II, in which alpha-helical turns break mediated by the rupture of groups of H-bonds.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Phase III is typically associated with large-deformation covalent bond stretching.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Alpha-helices in proteins may have low-frequency accordion-like motion as observed by the Raman spectroscopy and analyzed via the quasi-continuum model.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Helices not stabilized by tertiary interactions show dynamic behavior, which can be mainly attributed to helix fraying from the ends.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Homopolymers of amino acids (such as polylysine) can adopt α-helical structure at low temperature that is "melted out" at high temperatures.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] This **helix–coil transition** was once thought to be analogous to protein denaturation.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] The statistical mechanics of this transition can be modeled using an elegant transfer matrix method, characterized by two parameters: the propensity to initiate a helix and the propensity to extend a helix.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] At least five artists have made explicit reference to the α-helix in their work: Julie Newdoll in painting and Julian Voss-Andreae, Bathsheba Grossman, Byron Rubin, and Mike Tyka in sculpture.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] San Francisco area artist Julie Newdoll, who holds a degree in microbiology with a minor in art, has specialized in paintings inspired by microscopic images and molecules since 1990.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Her painting "Rise of the Alpha Helix" (2003) features human figures arranged in an α helical arrangement.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] According to the artist, "the flowers reflect the various types of sidechains that each amino acid holds out to the world".
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Julian Voss-Andreae is a German-born sculptor with degrees in experimental physics and sculpture.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Since 2001 Voss-Andreae creates "protein sculptures" based on protein structure with the α-helix being one of his preferred objects.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Voss-Andreae has made α-helix sculptures from diverse materials including bamboo and whole trees.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] A monument Voss-Andreae created in 2004 to celebrate the memory of Linus Pauling, the discoverer of the α-helix, is fashioned from a large steel beam rearranged in the structure of the α-helix.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] The 10-foot-tall (3 m), bright-red sculpture stands in front of Pauling's childhood home in Portland, Oregon.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Ribbon diagrams of α-helices are a prominent element in the laser-etched crystal sculptures of protein structures created by artist Bathsheba Grossman, such as those of insulin, hemoglobin, and DNA polymerase.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Byron Rubin is a former protein crystallographer now professional sculptor in metal of proteins, nucleic acids, and drug molecules – many of which featuring α-helices, such as subtilisin, human growth hormone, and phospholipase A2.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Mike Tyka is a computational biochemist at the University of Washington working with David Baker.
[src:protein-structure/alpha-helix] Tyka has been making sculptures of protein molecules since 2010 from copper and steel, including ubiquitin and a potassium channel tetramer.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] The **beta sheet** (**β-sheet**, also **β-pleated sheet**) is a common motif of the regular protein secondary structure.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] Beta sheets consist of **beta strands** (**β-strands**) connected laterally by at least two or three backbone hydrogen bonds, forming a generally twisted, pleated sheet.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] A β-strand is a stretch of polypeptide chain typically 3 to 10 amino acids long with backbone in an extended conformation.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] The supramolecular association of β-sheets has been implicated in the formation of the fibrils and protein aggregates observed in amyloidosis, Alzheimer's disease and other proteinopathies.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] The first β-sheet structure was proposed by William Astbury in the 1930s.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] He proposed the idea of hydrogen bonding between the peptide bonds of parallel or antiparallel extended β-strands.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] However, Astbury did not have the necessary data on the bond geometry of the amino acids in order to build accurate models, especially since he did not then know that the peptide bond was planar.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] A refined version was proposed by Linus Pauling and Robert Corey in 1951.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] Their model incorporated the planarity of the peptide bond which they previously explained as resulting from keto-enol tautomerization.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] The majority of β-strands are arranged adjacent to other strands and form an extensive hydrogen bond network with their neighbors in which the N−H groups in the backbone of one strand establish hydrogen bonds with the C=O groups in the backbone of the adjacent strands.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] In the fully extended β-strand, successive side chains point straight up and straight down in an alternating pattern.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] Adjacent β-strands in a β-sheet are aligned so that their Cα atoms are adjacent and their side chains point in the same direction.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] The "pleated" appearance of β-strands arises from tetrahedral chemical bonding at the Cα atom; for example, if a side chain points straight up, then the bonds to the C′ must point slightly downwards, since its bond angle is approximately 109.5°.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] The pleating causes the distance between Cα *i* and Cα *i* + 2 to be approximately 6 Å (0.60 nm), rather than the 7.6 Å (0.76 nm) expected from two fully extended *trans* peptides.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] The "sideways" distance between adjacent Cα atoms in hydrogen-bonded β-strands is roughly 5 Å (0.50 nm).
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] However, β-strands are rarely perfectly extended; rather, they exhibit a twist.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] The energetically preferred dihedral angles near (*φ*, *ψ*) = (–135°, 135°) (broadly, the upper left region of the Ramachandran plot) diverge significantly from the fully extended conformation (*φ*, *ψ*) = (–180°, 180°).
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] The twist is often associated with alternating fluctuations in the dihedral angles to prevent the individual β-strands in a larger sheet from splaying apart.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] A good example of a strongly twisted β-hairpin can be seen in the protein BPTI.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] The side chains point outwards from the folds of the pleats, roughly perpendicularly to the plane of the sheet; successive amino acid residues point outwards on alternating faces of the sheet.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] Because peptide chains have a directionality conferred by their N-terminus and C-terminus, β-strands too can be said to be directional.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] They are usually represented in protein topology diagrams by an arrow pointing toward the C-terminus.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] Adjacent β-strands can form hydrogen bonds in antiparallel, parallel, or mixed arrangements.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] In an antiparallel arrangement, the successive β-strands alternate directions so that the N-terminus of one strand is adjacent to the C-terminus of the next.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] This is the arrangement that produces the strongest inter-strand stability because it allows the inter-strand hydrogen bonds between carbonyls and amines to be planar, which is their preferred orientation.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] The peptide backbone dihedral angles (*φ*, *ψ*) are about (–140°, 135°) in antiparallel sheets.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] In this case, if two atoms Cα *i* and Cα *j* are adjacent in two hydrogen-bonded β-strands, then they form two mutual backbone hydrogen bonds to each other's flanking peptide groups; this is known as a **close pair** of hydrogen bonds.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] In a parallel arrangement, all of the N-termini of successive strands are oriented in the same direction; this orientation may be slightly less stable because it introduces nonplanarity in the inter-strand hydrogen bonding pattern.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] The dihedral angles (*φ*, *ψ*) are about (–120°, 115°) in parallel sheets.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] There is also evidence that parallel β-sheet may be more stable since small amyloidogenic sequences appear to generally aggregate into β-sheet fibrils composed of primarily parallel β-sheet strands, where one would expect anti-parallel fibrils if anti-parallel were more stable.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] In parallel β-sheet structure, if two atoms Cα *i* and Cα *j* are adjacent in two hydrogen-bonded β-strands, then they do *not* hydrogen bond to each other; rather, one residue forms hydrogen bonds to the residues that flank the other (but not vice versa).
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] For example, residue *i* may form hydrogen bonds to residues *j* − 1 and *j* + 1; this is known as a **wide pair** of hydrogen bonds.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] By contrast, residue *j* may hydrogen-bond to different residues altogether, or to none at all.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] The hydrogen bond arrangement in parallel beta sheet resembles that in an amide ring motif with 11 atoms.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] Finally, an individual strand may exhibit a mixed bonding pattern, with a parallel strand on one side and an antiparallel strand on the other.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] Also proteins are inherently constrained by folding kinetics as well as folding thermodynamics, so one must always be careful in concluding stability from bioinformatic analysis.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] The hydrogen bonding of β-strands need not be perfect, but can exhibit localized disruptions known as β-bulges.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] The hydrogen bonds lie roughly in the plane of the sheet, with the peptide carbonyl groups pointing in alternating directions with successive residues; for comparison, successive carbonyls point in the *same* direction in the alpha helix.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] Large aromatic residues (tyrosine, phenylalanine, tryptophan) and β-branched amino acids (threonine, valine, isoleucine) are favored to be found in β-strands in the *middle* of β-sheets.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] Different types of residues (such as proline) are likely to be found in the *edge* strands in β-sheets, presumably to avoid the "edge-to-edge" association between proteins that might lead to aggregation and amyloid formation.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] Individual strands can also be linked in more elaborate ways with longer loops that may contain α-helices.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] The Greek key motif consists of four adjacent antiparallel strands and their linking loops.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] It consists of three antiparallel strands connected by hairpins, while the fourth is adjacent to the first and linked to the third by a longer loop.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] This type of structure forms easily during the protein folding process.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] It was named after a pattern common to Greek ornamental artwork (see meander).
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] Due to the chirality of their component amino acids, all strands exhibit right-handed twist evident in most higher-order β-sheet structures.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] In particular, the linking loop between two parallel strands almost always has a right-handed crossover chirality, which is strongly favored by the inherent twist of the sheet.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] This linking loop frequently contains a helical region, in which case it is called a β-α-β motif.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] A closely related motif called a β-α-β-α motif forms the basic component of the most commonly observed protein tertiary structure, the TIM barrel.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] A simple supersecondary protein topology composed of two or more consecutive antiparallel β-strands linked together by hairpin loops.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] This motif is common in β-sheets and can be found in several structural architectures including β-barrels and β-propellers.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] The vast majority of β-meander regions in proteins are found packed against other motifs or sections of the polypeptide chain, forming portions of the hydrophobic core that canonically drives formation of the folded structure.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] However, several notable exceptions include the Outer Surface Protein A (OspA) variants and the Single Layer β-sheet Proteins (SLBPs) which contain single-layer β-sheets in the absence of a traditional hydrophobic core.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] These β-rich proteins feature an extended single-layer β-meander β-sheets that are primarily stabilized via inter-β-strand interactions and hydrophobic interactions present in the turn regions connecting individual strands.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] The psi-loop (Ψ-loop) motif consists of two antiparallel strands with one strand in between that is connected to both by hydrogen bonds.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] There are four possible strand topologies for single Ψ-loops.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] This motif is rare as the process resulting in its formation seems unlikely to occur during protein folding.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] The Ψ-loop was first identified in the aspartic protease family.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] β-sheets are present in all-β, α+β and α/β domains, and in many peptides or small proteins with poorly defined overall architecture.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] All-β domains may form β-barrels, β-sandwiches, β-prisms, β-propellers, and β-helices.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] The **topology** of a β-sheet describes the order of hydrogen-bonded β-strands along the backbone.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] For example, the flavodoxin fold has a five-stranded, parallel β-sheet with topology 21345; thus, the edge strands are β-strand 2 and β-strand 5 along the backbone.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] Spelled out explicitly, β-strand 2 is H-bonded to β-strand 1, which is H-bonded to β-strand 3, which is H-bonded to β-strand 4, which is H-bonded to β-strand 5, the other edge strand.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] In the same system, the Greek key motif described above has a 4123 topology.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] The secondary structure of a β-sheet can be described roughly by giving the number of strands, their topology, and whether their hydrogen bonds are parallel or antiparallel.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] β-sheets can be *open*, meaning that they have two edge strands (as in the flavodoxin fold or the immunoglobulin fold) or they can be *closed β-barrels* (such as the TIM barrel). β-Barrels are often described by their *stagger* or *shear*.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] Some open β-sheets are very curved and fold over on themselves (as in the SH3 domain) or form horseshoe shapes (as in the ribonuclease inhibitor).
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] Open β-sheets can assemble face-to-face (such as the β-propeller domain or immunoglobulin fold) or edge-to-edge, forming one big β-sheet.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] β-pleated sheet structures are made from extended β-strand polypeptide chains, with strands linked to their neighbours by hydrogen bonds.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] Due to this extended backbone conformation, β-sheets resist stretching. β-sheets in proteins may carry out low-frequency accordion-like motion as observed by the Raman spectroscopy and analyzed with the quasi-continuum model.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] A β-helix is formed from repeating structural units consisting of two or three short β-strands linked by short loops.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] These units "stack" atop one another in a helical fashion so that successive repetitions of the same strand hydrogen-bond with each other in a parallel orientation.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] See the β-helix article for further information.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] In lefthanded β-helices, the strands themselves are quite straight and untwisted; the resulting helical surfaces are nearly flat, forming a regular triangular prism shape, as shown for the 1QRE archaeal carbonic anhydrase at right.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] Other examples are the lipid A synthesis enzyme LpxA and insect antifreeze proteins with a regular array of Thr sidechains on one face that mimic the structure of ice.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] A two-sided β-helix (right-handed) is found in some bacterial metalloproteases; its two loops are each six residues long and bind stabilizing calcium ions to maintain the integrity of the structure, using the backbone and the Asp side chain oxygens of a GGXGXD sequence motif.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] This fold is called a β-roll in the SCOP classification.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] Some proteins that are disordered or helical as monomers, such as amyloid β (see amyloid plaque) can form β-sheet-rich oligomeric structures associated with pathological states.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] The amyloid β protein's oligomeric form is implicated as a cause of Alzheimer's.
[src:protein-structure/beta-sheet] Its structure has yet to be determined in full, but recent data suggest that it may resemble an unusual two-strand β-helix.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] In molecular biology, a **protein domain** is a region of a protein's polypeptide chain that is self-stabilizing and that folds independently from the rest.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Each domain forms a compact folded three-dimensional structure.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Many proteins consist of several domains, and a domain may appear in a variety of different proteins.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Molecular evolution uses domains as building blocks and these may be recombined in different arrangements to create proteins with different functions.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] In general, domains vary in length from between about 50 amino acids up to 250 amino acids in length.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] The shortest domains, such as zinc fingers, are stabilized by metal ions or disulfide bridges.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Domains often form functional units, such as the calcium-binding EF hand domain of calmodulin.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Because they are independently stable, domains can be "swapped" by genetic engineering between one protein and another to make chimeric proteins.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] The concept of the **domain** was first proposed in 1973 by Wetlaufer after X-ray crystallographic studies of hen lysozyme and papain and by limited proteolysis studies of immunoglobulins.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Wetlaufer defined domains as stable units of protein structure that could fold autonomously.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Each definition is valid and will often overlap, i.e. a compact structural domain that is found amongst diverse proteins is likely to fold independently within its structural environment.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Nature often brings several domains together to form multidomain and multifunctional proteins with a vast number of possibilities.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] In a multidomain protein, each domain may fulfill its own function independently, or in a concerted manner with its neighbours.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Domains can either serve as modules for building up large assemblies such as virus particles or muscle fibres, or can provide specific catalytic or binding sites as found in enzymes or regulatory proteins.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] An appropriate example is pyruvate kinase (see first figure), a glycolytic enzyme that plays an important role in regulating the flux from fructose-1,6-biphosphate to pyruvate.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] It contains an all-β nucleotide-binding domain (in blue), an α/β-substrate binding domain (in grey) and an α/β-regulatory domain (in olive green), connected by several polypeptide linkers.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Each domain in this protein occurs in diverse sets of protein families.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] The central α/β-barrel substrate binding domain is one of the most common enzyme folds.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] It is seen in many different enzyme families catalysing completely unrelated reactions.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] The α/β-barrel is commonly called the TIM barrel named after triose phosphate isomerase, which was the first such structure to be solved.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] It is currently classified into 26 homologous families in the CATH domain database.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] The TIM barrel is formed from a sequence of β-α-β motifs closed by the first and last strand hydrogen bonding together, forming an eight stranded barrel.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] There is debate about the evolutionary origin of this domain.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] One study has suggested that a single ancestral enzyme could have diverged into several families, while another suggests that a stable TIM-barrel structure has evolved through convergent evolution.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] The TIM-barrel in pyruvate kinase is 'discontinuous', meaning that more than one segment of the polypeptide is required to form the domain.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] This is likely to be the result of the insertion of one domain into another during the protein's evolution.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] It has been shown from known structures that about a quarter of structural domains are discontinuous.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] The inserted β-barrel regulatory domain is 'continuous', made up of a single stretch of polypeptide.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] The primary structure (string of amino acids) of a protein ultimately encodes its uniquely folded three-dimensional (3D) conformation.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] The most important factor governing the folding of a protein into 3D structure is the distribution of polar and non-polar side chains.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Folding is driven by the burial of hydrophobic side chains into the interior of the molecule so to avoid contact with the aqueous environment.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Generally proteins have a core of hydrophobic residues surrounded by a shell of hydrophilic residues.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Since the peptide bonds themselves are polar they are neutralised by hydrogen bonding with each other when in the hydrophobic environment.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] This gives rise to regions of the polypeptide that form regular 3D structural patterns called secondary structure.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] There are two main types of secondary structure: α-helices and β-sheets.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Some simple combinations of secondary structure elements have been found to frequently occur in protein structure and are referred to as supersecondary structure or motifs.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] For example, the β-hairpin motif consists of two adjacent antiparallel β-strands joined by a small loop.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] It is present in most antiparallel β structures both as an isolated ribbon and as part of more complex β-sheets.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Another common super-secondary structure is the β-α-β motif, which is frequently used to connect two parallel β-strands.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] The central α-helix connects the C-termini of the first strand to the N-termini of the second strand, packing its side chains against the β-sheet and therefore shielding the hydrophobic residues of the β-strands from the surface.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Covalent association of two domains represents a functional and structural advantage since there is an increase in stability when compared with the same structures non-covalently associated.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Other advantages are the protection of intermediates within inter-domain enzymatic clefts that may otherwise be unstable in aqueous environments, and a fixed stoichiometric ratio of the enzymatic activity necessary for a sequential set of reactions.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Structural alignment is an important tool for determining domains.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Several motifs pack together to form compact, local, semi-independent units called domains.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] The overall 3D structure of the polypeptide chain is referred to as the protein's tertiary structure.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Domains are the fundamental units of tertiary structure, each domain containing an individual hydrophobic core built from secondary structural units connected by loop regions.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] The packing of the polypeptide is usually much tighter in the interior than the exterior of the domain producing a solid-like core and a fluid-like surface.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Core residues are often conserved in a protein family, whereas the residues in loops are less conserved, unless they are involved in the protein's function.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Protein tertiary structure can be divided into four main classes based on the secondary structural content of the domain.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] The size of individual structural domains varies from 36 residues in E-selectin to 692 residues in lipoxygenase-1, but the majority, 90%, have fewer than 200 residues with an average of approximately 100 residues.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Very short domains, less than 40 residues, are often stabilised by metal ions or disulfide bonds.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Larger domains, greater than 300 residues, are likely to consist of multiple hydrophobic cores.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Many proteins have a quaternary structure, which consists of several polypeptide chains that associate into an oligomeric molecule.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Each polypeptide chain in such a protein is called a subunit.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Hemoglobin, for example, consists of two α and two β subunits.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Each of the four chains has an all-α globin fold with a heme pocket.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Domain swapping is a mechanism for forming oligomeric assemblies.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] In domain swapping, a secondary or tertiary element of a monomeric protein is replaced by the same element of another protein.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Domain swapping can range from secondary structure elements to whole structural domains.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] It also represents a model of evolution for functional adaptation by oligomerisation, e.g. oligomeric enzymes that have their active site at subunit interfaces.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Nature is a tinkerer and not an inventor, new sequences are adapted from pre-existing sequences rather than invented.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Domains are the common material used by nature to generate new sequences; they can be thought of as genetically mobile units, referred to as 'modules'.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Often, the C and N termini of domains are close together in space, allowing them to easily be "slotted into" parent structures during the process of evolution.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Many domain families are found in all three forms of life, Archaea, Bacteria and Eukarya.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Protein modules are a subset of protein domains which are found across a range of different proteins with a particularly versatile structure.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Examples can be found among extracellular proteins associated with clotting, fibrinolysis, complement, the extracellular matrix, cell surface adhesion molecules and cytokine receptors.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Four concrete examples of widespread protein modules are the following domains: SH2, immunoglobulin, fibronectin type 3 and the kringle.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Molecular evolution gives rise to families of related proteins with similar sequence and structure.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] However, sequence similarities can be extremely low between proteins that share the same structure.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Protein structures may be similar because proteins have diverged from a common ancestor.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Alternatively, some folds may be more favored than others as they represent stable arrangements of secondary structures and some proteins may converge towards these folds over the course of evolution.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] There are currently more than 200,000 experimentally determined protein 3D structures deposited within the Protein Data Bank (PDB).
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] However, this set contains many identical or very similar structures.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] All proteins should be classified to structural families to understand their evolutionary relationships.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Structural comparisons are best achieved at the domain level.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] For this reason many algorithms have been developed to automatically assign domains in proteins with known 3D structure (see § Domain definition from structural co-ordinates).
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] The CATH domain database classifies domains into approximately 800 fold families; ten of these folds are highly populated and are referred to as 'super-folds'.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Super-folds are defined as folds for which there are at least three structures without significant sequence similarity.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] The most populated is the α/β-barrel super-fold, as described previously.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] The majority of proteins, two-thirds in unicellular organisms and more than 80% in metazoa, are multidomain proteins.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] However, other studies concluded that 40% of prokaryotic proteins consist of multiple domains while eukaryotes have approximately 65% multi-domain proteins.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Many domains in eukaryotic multidomain proteins can be found as independent proteins in prokaryotes, suggesting that domains in multidomain proteins have once existed as independent proteins.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] For example, vertebrates have a multi-enzyme polypeptide containing the GAR synthetase, AIR synthetase and GAR transformylase domains (GARs-AIRs-GARt; GAR: glycinamide ribonucleotide synthetase/transferase; AIR: aminoimidazole ribonucleotide synthetase).
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] In insects, the polypeptide appears as GARs-(AIRs)2-GARt, in yeast GARs-AIRs is encoded separately from GARt, and in bacteria each domain is encoded separately.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Attractin-like protein 1 (ATRNL1) is a multi-domain protein found in animals, including humans.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Multidomain proteins are likely to have emerged from selective pressure during evolution to create new functions.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Various proteins have diverged from common ancestors by different combinations and associations of domains.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] The simplest multidomain organization seen in proteins is that of a single domain repeated in tandem.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] The domains may interact with each other (domain-domain interaction) or remain isolated, like beads on string.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] The giant 30,000 residue muscle protein titin comprises about 120 fibronectin-III-type and Ig-type domains.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] In the serine proteases, a gene duplication event has led to the formation of a two β-barrel domain enzyme.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] The repeats have diverged so widely that there is no obvious sequence similarity between them.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] The active site is located at a cleft between the two β-barrel domains, in which functionally important residues are contributed from each domain.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Genetically engineered mutants of the chymotrypsin serine protease were shown to have some proteinase activity even though their active site residues were abolished and it has therefore been postulated that the duplication event enhanced the enzyme's activity.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Modules frequently display different connectivity relationships, as illustrated by the kinesins and ABC transporters.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] The kinesin motor domain can be at either end of a polypeptide chain that includes a coiled-coil region and a cargo domain.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] ABC transporters are built with up to four domains consisting of two unrelated modules, ATP-binding cassette and an integral membrane module, arranged in various combinations.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Not only do domains recombine, but there are many examples of a domain having been inserted into another.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Sequence or structural similarities to other domains demonstrate that homologues of inserted and parent domains can exist independently.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] An example is that of the 'fingers' inserted into the 'palm' domain within the polymerases of the Pol I family.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Since a domain can be inserted into another, there should always be at least one continuous domain in a multidomain protein.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] This is the main difference between definitions of structural domains and evolutionary/functional domains.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] An evolutionary domain will be limited to one or two connections between domains, whereas structural domains can have unlimited connections, within a given criterion of the existence of a common core.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Several structural domains could be assigned to an evolutionary domain.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] A superdomain consists of two or more conserved domains of nominally independent origin, but subsequently inherited as a single structural/functional unit.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] This combined superdomain can occur in diverse proteins that are not related by gene duplication alone.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] An example of a superdomain is the protein tyrosine phosphatase–C2 domain pair in PTEN, tensin, auxilin and the membrane protein TPTE2.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] This superdomain is found in proteins in animals, plants and fungi.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] A key feature of the PTP-C2 superdomain is amino acid residue conservation in the domain interface.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Folding is a directed search of conformational space allowing the protein to fold on a biologically feasible time scale.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] The Levinthal paradox states that if an averaged sized protein would sample all possible conformations before finding the one with the lowest energy, the whole process would take billions of years.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Proteins typically fold within 0.1 and 1000 seconds.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Therefore, the protein folding process must be directed some way through a specific folding pathway.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] The forces that direct this search are likely to be a combination of local and global influences whose effects are felt at various stages of the reaction.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Advances in experimental and theoretical studies have shown that folding can be viewed in terms of energy landscapes, where folding kinetics is considered as a progressive organisation of an ensemble of partially folded structures through which a protein passes on its way to the folded structure.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] This has been described in terms of a folding funnel, in which an unfolded protein has a large number of conformational states available and there are fewer states available to the folded protein.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] A funnel implies that for protein folding there is a decrease in energy and loss of entropy with increasing tertiary structure formation.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] The local roughness of the funnel reflects kinetic traps, corresponding to the accumulation of misfolded intermediates.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] A folding chain progresses toward lower intra-chain free-energies by increasing its compactness.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] The chain's conformational options become increasingly narrowed ultimately toward one native structure.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] The organisation of large proteins by structural domains represents an advantage for protein folding, with each domain being able to individually fold, accelerating the folding process and reducing a potentially large combination of residue interactions.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Furthermore, given the observed random distribution of hydrophobic residues in proteins, domain formation appears to be the optimal solution for a large protein to bury its hydrophobic residues while keeping the hydrophilic residues at the surface.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] However, the role of inter-domain interactions in protein folding and in energetics of stabilisation of the native structure, probably differs for each protein.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] In T4 lysozyme, the influence of one domain on the other is so strong that the entire molecule is resistant to proteolytic cleavage.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] In this case, folding is a sequential process where the C-terminal domain is required to fold independently in an early step, and the other domain requires the presence of the folded C-terminal domain for folding and stabilisation.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] It has been found that the folding of an isolated domain can take place at the same rate or sometimes faster than that of the integrated domain, suggesting that unfavourable interactions with the rest of the protein can occur during folding.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Several arguments suggest that the slowest step in the folding of large proteins is the pairing of the folded domains.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] This is either because the domains are not folded entirely correctly or because the small adjustments required for their interaction are energetically unfavourable, such as the removal of water from the domain interface.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Protein domain dynamics play a key role in a multitude of molecular recognition and signaling processes.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Protein domains, connected by intrinsically disordered flexible linker domains, induce long-range allostery via protein domain dynamics.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] The resultant dynamic modes cannot be generally predicted from static structures of either the entire protein or individual domains.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] The importance of domains as structural building blocks and elements of evolution has brought about many automated methods for their identification and classification in proteins of known structure.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Automatic procedures for reliable domain assignment is essential for the generation of the domain databases, especially as the number of known protein structures is increasing.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Although the boundaries of a domain can be determined by visual inspection, construction of an automated method is not straightforward.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Problems occur when faced with domains that are discontinuous or highly associated.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] The fact that there is no standard definition of what a domain really is has meant that domain assignments have varied enormously, with each researcher using a unique set of criteria.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] A structural domain is a compact, globular sub-structure with more interactions within it than with the rest of the protein.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Therefore, a structural domain can be determined by two visual characteristics: its compactness and its extent of isolation.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Measures of local compactness in proteins have been used in many of the early methods of domain assignment and in several of the more recent methods.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] One of the first algorithms used a Cα-Cα distance map together with a hierarchical clustering routine that considered proteins as several small segments, 10 residues in length.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] The initial segments were clustered one after another based on inter-segment distances; segments with the shortest distances were clustered and considered as single segments thereafter.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] The stepwise clustering finally included the full protein.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Go also exploited the fact that inter-domain distances are normally larger than intra-domain distances; all possible Cα-Cα distances were represented as diagonal plots in which there were distinct patterns for helices, extended strands and combinations of secondary structures.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] The method by Sowdhamini and Blundell clusters secondary structures in a protein based on their Cα-Cα distances and identifies domains from the pattern in their dendrograms.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] As the procedure does not consider the protein as a continuous chain of amino acids there are no problems in treating discontinuous domains.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Specific nodes in these dendrograms are identified as tertiary structural clusters of the protein, these include both super-secondary structures and domains.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] The DOMAK algorithm is used to create the 3Dee domain database.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] It calculates a 'split value' from the number of each type of contact when the protein is divided arbitrarily into two parts.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] This split value is large when the two parts of the structure are distinct.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] The method of Wodak and Janin was based on the calculated interface areas between two chain segments repeatedly cleaved at various residue positions.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Interface areas were calculated by comparing surface areas of the cleaved segments with that of the native structure.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Potential domain boundaries can be identified at a site where the interface area was at a minimum.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Other methods have used measures of solvent accessibility to calculate compactness.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] The PUU algorithm incorporates a harmonic model used to approximate inter-domain dynamics.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] The underlying physical concept is that many rigid interactions will occur within each domain and loose interactions will occur between domains.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] This algorithm is used to define domains in the FSSP domain database.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Swindells (1995) developed a method, DETECTIVE, for identification of domains in protein structures based on the idea that domains have a hydrophobic interior.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Deficiencies were found to occur when hydrophobic cores from different domains continue through the interface region.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] RigidFinder is a novel method for identification of protein rigid blocks (domains and loops) from two different conformations.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Rigid blocks are defined as blocks where all inter residue distances are conserved across conformations.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] The method RIBFIND developed by Pandurangan and Topf identifies rigid bodies in protein structures by performing spacial clustering of secondary structural elements in proteins.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] The RIBFIND rigid bodies have been used to flexibly fit protein structures into cryo electron microscopy density maps.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] The method, termed PiSQRD, is publicly available in the form of a webserver.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] The latter allows users to optimally subdivide single-chain or multimeric proteins into quasi-rigid domains based on the collective modes of fluctuation of the system.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] By default the latter are calculated through an elastic network model; alternatively pre-calculated essential dynamical spaces can be uploaded by the user.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] A large fraction of domains are of unknown function.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] A **domain of unknown function** (DUF) is a protein domain that has no characterized function.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] These families have been collected together in the Pfam database using the prefix DUF followed by a number, with examples being DUF2992 and DUF1220.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] There are now over 3,000 DUF families within the Pfam database representing over 20% of known families.
[src:protein-structure/protein-domain] Surprisingly, the number of DUFs in Pfam has increased from 20% (in 2010) to 22% (in 2019), mostly due to an increasing number of new genome sequences.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] Secondary structure is formally defined by the pattern of hydrogen bonds between the amino hydrogen and carboxyl oxygen atoms in the peptide backbone.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] Secondary structure may alternatively be defined based on the regular pattern of backbone dihedral angles in a particular region of the Ramachandran plot regardless of whether it has the correct hydrogen bonds.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] The concept of secondary structure was introduced by Kaj Ulrik Linderstrøm-Lang at Stanford in 1952.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] Other types of biopolymers such as nucleic acids also possess characteristic secondary structures.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] The most common secondary structures are alpha helices and beta sheets.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] Other helices, such as the 310 helix and π helix, are calculated to have energetically favorable hydrogen-bonding patterns but are rarely observed in natural proteins except at the ends of α helices due to unfavorable backbone packing in the center of the helix.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] Other extended structures such as the polyproline helix and alpha sheet are rare in native state proteins but are often hypothesized as important protein folding intermediates.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] Tight turns and loose, flexible loops link the more "regular" secondary structure elements.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] The random coil is not a true secondary structure, but is the class of conformations that indicate an absence of regular secondary structure.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] Amino acids vary in their ability to form the various secondary structure elements.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] Turns and bends are preferred by glycine (G), asparagine (N), proline (P), aspartate (D) and serine (S), whereas the last two amino acids, cysteine (C) and histidine (H) show no preference.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] Besides this, proline and glycine are sometimes known as "helix breakers" because they disrupt the regularity of the α helical backbone conformation; However, these preferences are not strong enough to produce a reliable method of predicting secondary structure from sequence alone.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] Low frequency collective vibrations are thought to be sensitive to local rigidity within proteins, revealing beta structures to be generically more rigid than alpha or disordered proteins.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] Neutron scattering measurements have directly connected the spectral feature at ~1 THz to collective motions of the secondary structure of beta-barrel protein GFP.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] Hydrogen bonding patterns in secondary structures may be significantly distorted, which makes automatic determination of secondary structure difficult.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] There are several methods for formally defining protein secondary structure (e.g., DSSP, DEFINE, STRIDE, ScrewFit, SST).
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] The Dictionary of Protein Secondary Structure, in short DSSP, is commonly used to describe the protein secondary structure with single letter codes.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] The secondary structure is assigned based on hydrogen bonding patterns as those initially proposed by Pauling et al. in 1951 (before any protein structure had ever been experimentally determined).
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] 'Coil' is often codified as ' ' (space), C (coil) or '–' (dash).
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] The helices (G, H and I) and sheet conformations are all required to have a reasonable length.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] This means that 2 adjacent residues in the primary structure must form the same hydrogen bonding pattern.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] If the helix or sheet hydrogen bonding pattern is too short they are designated as T or B, respectively.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] Other protein secondary structure assignment categories exist (sharp turns, Omega loops, etc.), but they are less frequently used.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] Secondary structure is defined by hydrogen bonding, so the exact definition of a hydrogen bond is critical.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] The standard hydrogen-bond definition for secondary structure is that of DSSP, which is a purely electrostatic model.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] It assigns charges of ±*q*1 ≈ 0.42*e* to the carbonyl carbon and oxygen, respectively, and charges of ±*q*2 ≈ 0.20*e* to the amide hydrogen and nitrogen, respectively.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] According to DSSP, a hydrogen-bond exists if and only if *E* is less than −0.5 kcal/mol (−2.1 kJ/mol).
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] Although the DSSP formula is a relatively crude approximation of the *physical* hydrogen-bond energy, it is generally accepted as a tool for defining secondary structure.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] SST is a Bayesian method to assign secondary structure to protein coordinate data using the Shannon information criterion of Minimum Message Length (MML) inference.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] SST treats any assignment of secondary structure as a potential hypothesis that attempts to explain (compress) given protein coordinate data.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] The core idea is that the ***best*** secondary structural assignment is the one that can explain (compress) the coordinates of a given protein coordinates in the most economical way, thus linking the inference of secondary structure to lossless data compression.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] SST detects **π** and **310** helical caps to standard **α**-helices, and automatically assembles the various extended strands into consistent β-pleated sheets.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] It provides a readable output of dissected secondary structural elements, and a corresponding PyMol-loadable script to visualize the assigned secondary structural elements individually.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] The rough secondary-structure content of a biopolymer (e.g., "this protein is 40% α-helix and 20% β-sheet") can be estimated spectroscopically.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] For proteins, a common method is far-ultraviolet (far-UV, 170–250 nm) circular dichroism.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] A pronounced double minimum at 208 and 222 nm indicate α-helical structure, whereas a single minimum at 204 nm or 217 nm reflects random-coil or β-sheet structure, respectively.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] A less common method is infrared spectroscopy, which detects differences in the bond oscillations of amide groups due to hydrogen-bonding.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] Finally, secondary-structure contents may be estimated accurately using the chemical shifts of an initially unassigned NMR spectrum.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] Predicting protein tertiary structure from only its amino sequence is a very challenging problem (see protein structure prediction), but using the simpler secondary structure definitions is more tractable.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] Early methods of secondary-structure prediction were restricted to predicting the three predominate states: helix, sheet, or random coil.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] These methods were based on the helix- or sheet-forming propensities of individual amino acids, sometimes coupled with rules for estimating the free energy of forming secondary structure elements.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] The first widely used techniques to predict protein secondary structure from the amino acid sequence were the Chou–Fasman method and the GOR method.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] Although such methods claimed to achieve ~60% accurate in predicting which of the three states (helix/sheet/coil) a residue adopts, blind computing assessments later showed that the actual accuracy was much lower.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] For illustration, a given protein might have a glycine at a given position, which by itself might suggest a random coil there.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] However, multiple sequence alignment might reveal that helix-favoring amino acids occur at that position (and nearby positions) in 95% of homologous proteins spanning nearly a billion years of evolution.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] Moreover, by examining the average hydrophobicity at that and nearby positions, the same alignment might also suggest a pattern of residue solvent accessibility consistent with an α-helix.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] Taken together, these factors would suggest that the glycine of the original protein adopts α-helical structure, rather than random coil.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] Several types of methods are used to combine all the available data to form a 3-state prediction, including neural networks, hidden Markov models and support vector machines.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] Modern prediction methods also provide a confidence score for their predictions at every position.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] Secondary-structure prediction methods were evaluated by the Critical Assessment of protein Structure Prediction (CASP) experiments and continuously benchmarked, e.g. by EVA (benchmark).
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] Based on these tests, the most accurate methods were Psipred, SAM, PORTER, PROF, and SABLE.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] The chief area for improvement appears to be the prediction of β-strands; residues confidently predicted as β-strand are likely to be so, but the methods are apt to overlook some β-strand segments (false negatives).
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] There is likely an upper limit of ~90% prediction accuracy overall, due to the idiosyncrasies of the standard method (DSSP) for assigning secondary-structure classes (helix/strand/coil) to PDB structures, against which the predictions are benchmarked.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] Accurate secondary-structure prediction is a key element in the prediction of tertiary structure, in all but the simplest (homology modeling) cases.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] For example, a confidently predicted pattern of six secondary structure elements βαββαβ is the signature of a ferredoxin fold.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] Both protein and nucleic acid secondary structures can be used to aid in multiple sequence alignment.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] These alignments can be made more accurate by the inclusion of secondary structure information in addition to simple sequence information.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] This is sometimes less useful in RNA because base pairing is much more highly conserved than sequence.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] Distant relationships between proteins whose primary structures are unalignable can sometimes be found by secondary structure.
[src:protein-structure/protein-secondary-structure] It has been shown that α-helices are more stable, robust to mutations, and designable than β-strands in natural proteins, thus designing functional all-α proteins is likely to be easier that designing proteins with both helices and strands; this has been recently confirmed experimentally.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Protein structures range in size from tens to several thousand amino acids.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] By physical size, proteins are classified as nanoparticles, between 1–100 nm.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Very large protein complexes can be formed from protein subunits.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] For example, many thousands of actin molecules assemble into a microfilament.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] A protein usually undergoes reversible structural changes in performing its biological function.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] The alternative structures of the same protein are referred to as different conformations, and transitions between them are called conformational changes.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] There are four distinct levels of protein structure.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] The primary structure of a protein refers to the sequence of amino acids in the polypeptide chain.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] The primary structure is held together by peptide bonds that are made during the process of protein biosynthesis.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] The two ends of the polypeptide chain are referred to as the carboxyl terminus (C-terminus) and the amino terminus (N-terminus) based on the nature of the free group on each extremity.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Counting of residues always starts at the N-terminal end (NH2-group), which is the end where the amino group is not involved in a peptide bond.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] The primary structure of a protein is determined by the gene corresponding to the protein.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] A specific sequence of nucleotides in DNA is transcribed into mRNA, which is read by the ribosome in a process called translation.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] The sequence of amino acids in insulin was discovered by Frederick Sanger, establishing that proteins have defining amino acid sequences.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] The sequence of a protein is unique to that protein, and defines the structure and function of the protein.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] The sequence of a protein can be determined by methods such as Edman degradation or tandem mass spectrometry.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Often, however, it is read directly from the sequence of the gene using the genetic code.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] It is strictly recommended to use the words "amino acid residues" when discussing proteins because when a peptide bond is formed, a water molecule is lost, and therefore proteins are made up of amino acid residues.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Post-translational modifications such as phosphorylations and glycosylations are usually also considered a part of the primary structure, and cannot be read from the gene.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] For example, insulin is composed of 51 amino acids in 2 chains.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] One chain has 31 amino acids, and the other has 20 amino acids.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Secondary structure refers to highly regular local sub-structures on the actual polypeptide backbone chain.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Two main types of secondary structure, the α-helix and the β-strand or β-sheets, were suggested in 1951 by Linus Pauling.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] These secondary structures are defined by patterns of hydrogen bonds between the main-chain peptide groups.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] They have a regular geometry, being constrained to specific values of the dihedral angles ψ and φ on the Ramachandran plot.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Both the α-helix and the β-sheet represent a way of saturating all the hydrogen bond donors and acceptors in the peptide backbone.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Some parts of the protein are ordered but do not form any regular structures.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] They should not be confused with random coil, an unfolded polypeptide chain lacking any fixed three-dimensional structure.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Several sequential secondary structures may form a "supersecondary unit".
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Tertiary structure refers to the three-dimensional structure created by a single protein molecule (a single polypeptide chain).
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] The α-helices and β-pleated-sheets are folded into a compact globular structure.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] The disulfide bonds are extremely rare in cytosolic proteins, since the cytosol (intracellular fluid) is generally a reducing environment.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Quaternary structure is the three-dimensional structure consisting of the aggregation of two or more individual polypeptide chains (subunits) that operate as a single functional unit (multimer).
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] The resulting multimer is stabilized by the same non-covalent interactions and disulfide bonds as in tertiary structure.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] There are many possible quaternary structure organisations.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Complexes of two or more polypeptides (i.e. multiple subunits) are called multimers.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Specifically it would be called a dimer if it contains two subunits, a trimer if it contains three subunits, a tetramer if it contains four subunits, and a pentamer if it contains five subunits, and so forth.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] The subunits are frequently related to one another by symmetry operations, such as a 2-fold axis in a dimer.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Multimers made up of identical subunits are referred to with a prefix of "homo-" and those made up of different subunits are referred to with a prefix of "hetero-", for example, a heterotetramer, such as the two alpha and two beta chains of hemoglobin.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] An assemblage of multiple copies of a particular polypeptide chain can be described as a homomer, multimer or oligomer.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Hundreds of proteins have been identified as being assembled into homomers in human cells.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Homomer formation may be driven by interaction between nascent polypeptide chains as they are translated from mRNA by nearby adjacent ribosomes.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Proteins are frequently described as consisting of several structural units.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] These units include domains, motifs, and folds.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Despite the fact that there are about 100,000 different proteins expressed in eukaryotic systems, there are many fewer different domains, structural motifs and folds.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] A structural domain is an element of the protein's overall structure that is self-stabilizing and often folds independently of the rest of the protein chain.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Many domains are not unique to the protein products of one gene or one gene family but instead appear in a variety of proteins.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Domains often are named and singled out because they figure prominently in the biological function of the protein they belong to; for example, the "calcium-binding domain of calmodulin".
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Because they are independently stable, domains can be "swapped" by genetic engineering between one protein and another to make chimera proteins.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] A conservative combination of several domains that occur in different proteins, such as protein tyrosine phosphatase domain and C2 domain pair, was called "a superdomain" that may evolve as a single unit.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Tertiary protein structures can have multiple secondary elements on the same polypeptide chain.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] The supersecondary structure refers to a specific combination of secondary structure elements, such as β-α-β units or a helix-turn-helix motif.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Some of them may be also referred to as structural motifs.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] A protein fold refers to the general protein architecture, like a helix bundle, β-barrel, Rossmann fold or different "folds" provided in the Structural Classification of Proteins database.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Proteins are not static objects, but rather populate ensembles of conformational states.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Transitions between these states typically occur on nanoscales, and have been linked to functionally relevant phenomena such as allosteric signaling and enzyme catalysis.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Protein dynamics and conformational changes allow proteins to function as nanoscale biological machines within cells, often in the form of multi-protein complexes.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Proteins are often thought of as relatively stable tertiary structures that experience conformational changes after being affected by interactions with other proteins or as a part of enzymatic activity.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] However, proteins may have varying degrees of stability, and some of the less stable variants are intrinsically disordered proteins.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] These proteins exist and function in a relatively 'disordered' state lacking a stable tertiary structure.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] As a result, they are difficult to describe by a single fixed tertiary structure.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Conformational ensembles have been devised as a way to provide a more accurate and 'dynamic' representation of the conformational state of intrinsically disordered proteins.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Protein ensemble files are a representation of a protein that can be considered to have a flexible structure.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Creating these files requires determining which of the various theoretically possible protein conformations actually exist.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] One approach is to apply computational algorithms to the protein data in order to try to determine the most likely set of conformations for an ensemble file.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] There are multiple methods for preparing data for the Protein Ensemble Database that fall into two general methodologies – pool and molecular dynamics (MD) approaches (diagrammed in the figure).
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] The pool based approach uses the protein's amino acid sequence to create a massive pool of random conformations.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] This pool is then subjected to more computational processing that creates a set of theoretical parameters for each conformation based on the structure.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Conformational subsets from this pool whose average theoretical parameters closely match known experimental data for this protein are selected.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] The alternative molecular dynamics approach takes multiple random conformations at a time and subjects all of them to experimental data.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Here the experimental data is serving as limitations to be placed on the conformations (e.g. known distances between atoms).
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Only conformations that manage to remain within the limits set by the experimental data are accepted.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] This approach often applies large amounts of experimental data to the conformations which is a very computationally demanding task.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Protein folding is the physical process describing how a polypeptide chain folds into a stable biologically functioning 3D-structure known as the native state.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] It happens after the polypeptide is synthesized by the ribosome.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] In some cases this happens co-translationally, where the nascent chain begins to fold while the rest of the polypeptide is being synthesized.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] In other cases, chaperone proteins can assists the folding.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] The structure of the native state is generally assumed to be determined by its amino acid sequence (Anfinsen's dogma).
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] This is a thermodynamic principle which states that the native structure is a unique, stable and kinetically accessible minimum of the free energy.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] The thermodynamic path going from unfolded to the native state is typically visualized as a free energy landscape in the form of a folding funnel.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] The forces driving the folding is a combination of hydrophobic interacts, hydrogen bonding, van der Waals forces and Coloumb interactions.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] During folding, the number hydrophobic side-chains exposed to water is minimized, which is known as hydrophobic collapse, causing them to collapse into the core of the protein.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] This causes most globular proteins to have hydrophilic side-chains outwards on the surface exposed to solvent and hydrophobic side-chains in the core.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Thermodynamic stability of proteins represents the free energy difference between the folded and unfolded protein states.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] This free energy difference is very sensitive to temperature, hence a change in temperature may result in unfolding or denaturation.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Protein denaturation may result in loss of function, and loss of native state.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] The free energy of stabilization of soluble globular proteins typically does not exceed 50 kJ/mol.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Taking into consideration the large number of hydrogen bonds that take place for the stabilization of secondary structures, and the stabilization of the inner core through hydrophobic interactions, the free energy of stabilization emerges as small difference between large numbers.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Around 90% of the protein structures available in the Protein Data Bank have been determined by X-ray crystallography.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] This method allows one to measure the three-dimensional (3-D) density distribution of electrons in the protein, in the crystallized state, and thereby infer the 3-D coordinates of all the atoms to be determined to a certain resolution.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Roughly 7% of the known protein structures have been obtained by nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) techniques.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] For larger protein complexes, cryo-electron microscopy can determine protein structures.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] The resolution is typically lower than that of X-ray crystallography, or NMR, but the maximum resolution is steadily increasing.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] This technique is still a particularly valuable for very large protein complexes such as virus coat proteins and amyloid fibers.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] General secondary structure composition can be determined via circular dichroism.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Vibrational spectroscopy can also be used to characterize the conformation of peptides, polypeptides, and proteins.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Two-dimensional infrared spectroscopy has become a valuable method to investigate the structures of flexible peptides and proteins that cannot be studied with other methods.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] A more qualitative picture of protein structure is often obtained by proteolysis, which is also useful to screen for more crystallizable protein samples.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Novel implementations of this approach, including fast parallel proteolysis (FASTpp), can probe the structured fraction and its stability without the need for purification.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Once a protein's structure has been experimentally determined, further detailed studies can be done computationally, using molecular dynamic simulations of that structure.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] A protein structure database is a database that is modeled around the various experimentally determined protein structures.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] The aim of most protein structure databases is to organize and annotate the protein structures, providing the biological community access to the experimental data in a useful way.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Data included in protein structure databases often includes 3D coordinates as well as experimental information, such as unit cell dimensions and angles for x-ray crystallography determined structures.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Protein structure databases are critical for many efforts in computational biology such as structure based drug design, both in developing the computational methods used and in providing a large experimental dataset used by some methods to provide insights about the function of a protein.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Protein structures can be grouped based on their structural similarity, topological class or a common evolutionary origin.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] The Structural Classification of Proteins database and CATH database provide two different structural classifications of proteins.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] When the structural similarity is large the two proteins have possibly diverged from a common ancestor, and shared structure between proteins is considered evidence of homology.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Structure similarity can then be used to group proteins together into protein superfamilies.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] If shared structure is significant but the fraction shared is small, the fragment shared may be the consequence of a more dramatic evolutionary event such as horizontal gene transfer, and joining proteins sharing these fragments into protein superfamilies is no longer justified.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Topology of a protein can be used to classify proteins as well.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Knot theory and circuit topology are two topology frameworks developed for classification of protein folds based on chain crossing and intrachain contacts respectively.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] The generation of a protein sequence is much easier than the determination of a protein structure.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] However, the structure of a protein gives much more insight in the function of the protein than its sequence.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Therefore, a number of methods for the computational prediction of protein structure from its sequence have been developed.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] *Ab initio* prediction methods use just the sequence of the protein.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Threading and homology modeling methods can build a 3-D model for a protein of unknown structure from experimental structures of evolutionarily-related proteins, called a protein family.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Predictive machine learning-based approaches tackle the structure problem at multiple levels.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] At the 1D level, secondary structure and solvent accessibility are predicted.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] The 2D level works on distances and points of contact along the protein chain; these predictions are orientation independent.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] At the 3D level, the coordinates of all the atoms in the protein are estimated; this level is the primary goal of most prediction efforts.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Finally, the 4D level predicts complexes of multiple proteins.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] Progress at these levels is assessed annually at the biannual Critical Assessment of Structure Prediction event.
[src:protein-structure/protein-structure] The results from structure studies can be fed in to machine learning techniques deployed to understand protein-protein interactions.
[src:protein-structure/protein-tertiary-structure] The science of the tertiary structure of proteins has progressed from one of hypothesis to one of detailed definition.
[src:protein-structure/protein-tertiary-structure] Although Emil Fischer had suggested proteins were made of polypeptide chains and amino acid side chains, it was Dorothy Maud Wrinch who incorporated geometry into the prediction of protein structures.
[src:protein-structure/protein-tertiary-structure] Wrinch demonstrated this with the *Cyclol* model, the first prediction of the structure of a globular protein.
[src:protein-structure/protein-tertiary-structure] Under favorable conditions, such as confident knowledge of secondary structure, contemporary methods are sometimes able to predict the tertiary structure of small proteins (<120 residues) *de novo* to within 5 Å (0.5 nm).
[src:protein-structure/protein-tertiary-structure] A protein folded into its native state or native conformation typically has a lower Gibbs free energy (a combination of enthalpy and entropy) than the unfolded conformation.
[src:protein-structure/protein-tertiary-structure] A protein will tend towards low-energy conformations, which will determine the protein's fold in the cellular environment.
[src:protein-structure/protein-tertiary-structure] Because many similar conformations will have similar energies, protein structures are dynamic, fluctuating between these similar structures.
[src:protein-structure/protein-tertiary-structure] Globular proteins have a core of hydrophobic amino acid residues and a surface region of water-exposed, charged, hydrophilic residues.
[src:protein-structure/protein-tertiary-structure] This arrangement may stabilize interactions within the tertiary structure.
[src:protein-structure/protein-tertiary-structure] For example, in secreted proteins, which are not bathed in cytoplasm, disulfide bonds between cysteine residues help to maintain the tertiary structure.
[src:protein-structure/protein-tertiary-structure] There is a commonality of stable tertiary structures seen in proteins of diverse function and diverse evolution.
[src:protein-structure/protein-tertiary-structure] For example, the TIM barrel, named for the enzyme triosephosphateisomerase, is a common tertiary structure as is the highly stable, dimeric, coiled coil structure.
[src:protein-structure/protein-tertiary-structure] Hence, proteins may be classified by the structures they hold.
[src:protein-structure/protein-tertiary-structure] Databases of proteins which use such a classification include *SCOP* and *CATH*.
[src:protein-structure/protein-tertiary-structure] Folding kinetics may trap a protein in a high-energy conformation, i.e. a high-energy intermediate conformation blocks access to the lowest-energy conformation.
[src:protein-structure/protein-tertiary-structure] The high-energy conformation may contribute to the function of the protein.
[src:protein-structure/protein-tertiary-structure] For example, the influenza hemagglutinin protein is a single polypeptide chain which when activated, is proteolytically cleaved to form two polypeptide chains.
[src:protein-structure/protein-tertiary-structure] The two chains are held in a high-energy conformation.
[src:protein-structure/protein-tertiary-structure] When the local pH drops, the protein undergoes an energetically favorable conformational rearrangement that enables it to penetrate the host cell membrane.
[src:protein-structure/protein-tertiary-structure] Some tertiary protein structures may exist in long-lived states that are not the expected most stable state.
[src:protein-structure/protein-tertiary-structure] For example, many serpins (serine protease inhibitors) show this metastability.
[src:protein-structure/protein-tertiary-structure] They undergo a conformational change when a loop of the protein is cut by a protease.
[src:protein-structure/protein-tertiary-structure] It is commonly assumed that the native state of a protein is also the most thermodynamically stable and that a protein will reach its native state, given its chemical kinetics, before it is translated.
[src:protein-structure/protein-tertiary-structure] Protein chaperones within the cytoplasm of a cell assist a newly synthesised polypeptide to attain its native state.
[src:protein-structure/protein-tertiary-structure] Prediction of protein tertiary structure relies on knowing the protein's primary structure and comparing the possible predicted tertiary structure with known tertiary structures in protein data banks.
[src:protein-structure/protein-tertiary-structure] This only takes into account the cytoplasmic environment present at the time of protein synthesis to the extent that a similar cytoplasmic environment may also have influenced the structure of the proteins recorded in the protein data bank.
[src:protein-structure/protein-tertiary-structure] The structure of a protein, such as an enzyme, may change upon binding of its natural ligands, for example a cofactor.
[src:protein-structure/protein-tertiary-structure] In this case, the structure of the protein bound to the ligand is known as holo structure, while the unbound protein has an apo structure.
[src:protein-structure/protein-tertiary-structure] The knowledge of the tertiary structure of soluble globular proteins is more advanced than that of membrane proteins because the former are easier to study with available technology.
[src:protein-structure/protein-tertiary-structure] X-ray crystallography is the most common tool used to determine protein structure.
[src:protein-structure/protein-tertiary-structure] It provides high resolution of the structure but it does not give information about protein's conformational flexibility.
[src:protein-structure/protein-tertiary-structure] Protein NMR gives comparatively lower resolution of protein structure.
[src:protein-structure/protein-tertiary-structure] However, it can provide information about conformational changes of a protein in solution.
[src:protein-structure/protein-tertiary-structure] Cryogenic electron microscopy (cryo-EM) can give information about both a protein's tertiary and quaternary structure.
[src:protein-structure/protein-tertiary-structure] It is particularly well-suited to large proteins and symmetrical complexes of protein subunits.
[src:protein-structure/protein-tertiary-structure] Dual polarisation interferometry provides complementary information about surface captured proteins.
[src:protein-structure/protein-tertiary-structure] It assists in determining structure and conformation changes over time.
[src:protein-structure/protein-tertiary-structure] The Folding@home project at the University of Pennsylvania is a distributed computing research effort which uses approximately 5 petaFLOPS (≈10 x86 petaFLOPS) of available computing.
[src:protein-structure/protein-tertiary-structure] It aims to find an algorithm which will consistently predict protein tertiary and quaternary structures given the protein's amino acid sequence and its cellular conditions.
[src:protein-structure/protein-tertiary-structure] A list of software for protein tertiary structure prediction can be found at List of protein structure prediction software.
[src:protein-structure/ramachandran-plot] In biochemistry, a **Ramachandran plot** (also known as a **Rama plot**, a **Ramachandran diagram** or a **[φ,ψ] plot**), originally developed in 1963 by G.
[src:protein-structure/ramachandran-plot] Sasisekharan, is a way to visualize energetically allowed regions for backbone dihedral angles (also called as torsional angles, phi and psi angles) φ against ψ of amino acid residues in protein structure.
[src:protein-structure/ramachandran-plot] The figure on the left illustrates the definition of the φ and ψ backbone dihedral angles (called φ and φ' by Ramachandran).
[src:protein-structure/ramachandran-plot] The ω angle at the peptide bond is normally 180°, since the partial-double-bond character keeps the peptide bond planar.
[src:protein-structure/ramachandran-plot] The figure in the top right shows the allowed φ,ψ backbone conformational regions from the Ramachandran et al.
[src:protein-structure/ramachandran-plot] 1963 and 1968 hard-sphere calculations: full radius in solid outline, reduced radius in dashed, and relaxed tau (N-Cα-C) angle in dotted lines.
[src:protein-structure/ramachandran-plot] Because dihedral angle values are circular and 0° is the same as 360°, the edges of the Ramachandran plot "wrap" right-to-left and bottom-to-top.
[src:protein-structure/ramachandran-plot] For instance, the small strip of allowed values along the lower-left edge of the plot are a continuation of the large, extended-chain region at upper left.
[src:protein-structure/ramachandran-plot] A Ramachandran plot can be used in two somewhat different ways.
[src:protein-structure/ramachandran-plot] One is to show in theory which values, or conformations, of the ψ and φ angles are possible for an amino-acid residue in a protein (as at top right).
[src:protein-structure/ramachandran-plot] A second is to show the empirical distribution of datapoints observed in a single structure (as at right, here) in usage for structure validation, or else in a database of many structures (as in the lower 3 plots at left).
[src:protein-structure/ramachandran-plot] It's used to predict about Drug-ligand interaction and helpful in pharmaceutical industries.
[src:protein-structure/ramachandran-plot] Either case is usually shown against outlines for the theoretically favored regions.
[src:protein-structure/ramachandran-plot] One might expect that larger side chains would result in more restrictions and consequently a smaller allowable region in the Ramachandran plot, but the effect of side chains is small.
[src:protein-structure/ramachandran-plot] In practice, the major effect seen is that of the presence or absence of the methylene group at Cβ.
[src:protein-structure/ramachandran-plot] Glycine has only a hydrogen atom for its side chain, with a much smaller van der Waals radius than the CH3, CH2, or CH group that starts the side chain of all other amino acids.
[src:protein-structure/ramachandran-plot] Hence it is least restricted, and this is apparent in the Ramachandran plot for glycine (see Gly plot in gallery) for which the allowable area is considerably larger.
[src:protein-structure/ramachandran-plot] In contrast, the Ramachandran plot for proline, with its 5-membered-ring side chain connecting Cα to backbone N, shows a limited number of possible combinations of ψ and φ (see Pro plot in gallery).
[src:protein-structure/ramachandran-plot] The residue preceding proline ("pre-proline") also has limited combinations compared to the general case.
[src:protein-structure/ramachandran-plot] The first Ramachandran plot was calculated just after the first protein structure at atomic resolution was determined (myoglobin, in 1960), although the conclusions were based on small-molecule crystallography of short peptides.
[src:protein-structure/ramachandran-plot] Now, many decades later, there are tens of thousands of high-resolution protein structures determined by X-ray crystallography and deposited in the Protein Data Bank (PDB).
[src:protein-structure/ramachandran-plot] Many studies have taken advantage of this data to produce more detailed and accurate φ,ψ plots (e.g., Morris et al.
[src:protein-structure/ramachandran-plot] The four figures below show the datapoints from a large set of high-resolution structures and contours for favored and for allowed conformational regions for the general case (all amino acids except Gly, Pro, and pre-Pro), for Gly, and for Pro.
[src:protein-structure/ramachandran-plot] The most common regions are labeled: α for α helix, Lα for left-handed helix, β for β-sheet, and ppII for polyproline II.
[src:protein-structure/ramachandran-plot] While the Ramachandran plot has been a textbook resource for explaining the structural behavior of peptide bond, an exhaustive exploration of how a peptide behaves in every region of the Ramachandran plot was only recently published (Mannige 2017).
[src:protein-structure/ramachandran-plot] The Molecular Biophysics Unit at Indian Institute of Science celebrated 50 years of Ramachandran Map by organizing International Conference on Biomolecular Forms and Functions from 8–11 January 2013.
[src:protein-structure/ramachandran-plot] One can also plot the dihedral angles in polysaccharides (e.g. with CARP Archived 2019-05-05 at the Wayback Machine).
